The count of such elements is stored in bb[a]. Then, they insert a into aa at position j, which is determined by finding where the number of elements >= a + k equals bb[a]. Wait, the code says: while (bb[a] > 0) {
    if (aa[j] >= a +k) bb[a]--;
    j++;
}

So for each a, j starts at 0. For each j in aa (from 0 upwards), if aa[j] >= a +k, then decrement bb[a].

The code then computes j in 1-based, where to insert a_java into the aa array. The inner loop in Java:

int j = 0;
while (bb[a] >0) {
    if (aa[j] >= a +k) bb[a]--;
    j++;
}

So the loop checks each element in the current aa array (from 0 to m-1) until the condition is met. But in Fortran, the current aa array is from 1 to m (since m is the current size). So in Fortran, j starts at 1.
